properties.Title: Blizzard Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Blizzard conditions with poor visibility in snow and blowing snow are expected or occurring. A potent winter storm will impact southern Baffin Island and northern Kivalliq beginning late this afternoon. This storm will bring significant winds, with gusts in excess of 90 km/h likely. This system will also bring 10 to 20 cm of snow to some communities. These winds combined with falling snow will lead to significantly reduced visibilities in blowing snow, creating blizzard conditions. Conditions will gradually improve Sunday evening for southern Baffin Island and on Monday for northern Kivalliq. ### Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility. Blizzard warnings are issued when widespread reduced visibilities of 400 metres or less are expected for at least 6 hours. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NUstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NUStorm.

properties.Title: Snow Squall Watch In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow squalls possible today. An intense snow squall is forecast to shift northward out of New York State this morning and may move into southern portions of the Niagara Peninsula near Fort Erie. Locally heavy snowfall and reduced visibilities in blowing snow are possible before the snow squall drifts back southward later in the afternoon. A Snow Squall Warning may be required as the event draws nearer. Hazards: Locally 5 to 10 cm of snow by this afternoon Quickly accumulating snow at times Poor visibility in heavy snow and blowing snow Possible Impacts: Hazardous travel, particularly near Fort Erie. ### Travel may be hazardous due to sudden changes in the weather. Snow squall watches are issued when conditions are favourable for the formation of bands of snow that could produce intense accumulating snow or near zero visibilities. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

A low pressure system off Vancouver Island will move through the Alberni Valley and into the Strait of Georgia early Saturday morning giving a brief period of strong and gusty winds. Southeast winds of 70 gusting to 90 km/h are expected to develop in the early morning hours for areas adjacent to the Strait of Georgia along East Vancouver Island from Nanoose Bay to Campbell River. These winds will change to southwest and abate by late morning. Additionally, as the low pressure system transits the Alberni Valley, gusty southwest winds are expected within the valley. The southwest winds should remain below warning criteria. As these winds exit the Alberni Valley and reach East Vancouver Island, the gusty southwest winds will be felt from Qualicum beach to Fanny Bay ### Loose objects may be tossed by the wind and cause injury or damage. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.

properties.Title: Wind Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Strong winds that may cause damage are expected or occurring. A potent winter storm is set to impact Baffin Island later today and through to Monday. This weather system will bring the potential for wind gusts in excess of 90 km/h to Pangnirtung beginning early Sunday morning and persisting through the day. Winds will gradually diminish Sunday evening. Some snow is forecast with this system as well, which combined with the strong winds will create reduced visibilities in blowing snow. Confidence is relatively high that these significant wind gusts will materialize, but there is still some uncertainty in regards to the track of the system, so this warning may be adjusted as the system approaches. Please stay alert for updated bulletins. ### Damage to buildings, such as to roof shingles and windows, may occur. Loose objects may be tossed by the wind and cause injury or damage. Wind warnings are issued when there is a significant risk of damaging winds. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NUstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NUStorm.
